When processing emails, JIRA may consume excessive amounts of memory if the inbox contains a large number of messages.

In the MailFetcherService JIRA uses a call "folder.getMessages()".  It may be possible to handle the messages in chunks.  Refer http://forums.sun.com/thread.jspa?threadID=183353 which says in part
{quote}
folder.getMessages returns an array of javax.mail.Message objects but all objects are empty, when methos as getAllHeaders() or getContent() are called on a message, the attributes are filled in that object, so the phisical size of this array increasses with each processed mesage. Try to use folder.getMessages(int begin, int end) for chunks of 1000 mails. 
{quote}

